s -- tAppendix: The Origins of Neoliberalism and the Chile Project -- tNotes -- tBibliography and Archival Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow Chile became home to the world’s most radical free-market experiment—and what its downfall suggests about the fate of neoliberalism around the globeIn The Chile Project, Sebastian Edwards tells the remarkable story of how the neoliberal economic model—installed in Chile during the Pinochet dictatorship and deepened during three decades of left-of-center governments—came to an end in 2021, when Gabriel Boric, a young former student activist, was elected president, vowing that “If Chile was the cradle of neoliberalism, it will also be its grave.” More than a story about one Latin American country, The Chile Project is a behind-the-scenes history of the spread and consequences of the free-market thinking that dominated economic policymaking around the world in the second half of the twentieth century—but is now on the retreat.In 1955, the U.S. State Department launched the “Chile Project” to train Chilean economists at the University of Chicago, home of the libertarian Milton Friedman. After General Augusto Pinochet overthrew socialist president Salvador Allende in 1973, Chile’s “Chicago Boys” implemented the purest neoliberal model in the world for the next seventeen years, undertaking a sweeping package of privatization and deregulation, creating a modern capitalist economy, and sparking talk of a “Chilean miracle.” But under the veneer of success, a profound dissatisfaction with the vast inequalities caused by neoliberalism was growing. In 2019, protests erupted throughout the country, and in 2022 Boric began his presidency with a clear mandate: to end neoliberalismo.In telling the fascinating story of the Chicago Boys and Chile’s free-market revolution, The Chile Project provides an important new perspective on the history of neoliberalism and its global decline today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChicago school of economics. 0aNeoliberalismzChile. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aAbsentee Owner.  aActivism.  aAddendum.  aAdviser.  aAftermath of World War II.  aArnold Harberger.  aAuction.  aAugusto Pinochet.  aBankruptcy.  aBourgeois Dignity.  aBusiness school.  aCapitalism.  aCarlos Salinas de Gortari.  aCentral bank.  aChicago Boys.  aChicago school of economics.  aCommittee on Social Thought.  aCredibility.  aCurator.  aCurrency.  aDebt.  aDemocratic Revolution.  aDictatorship.  aDissident.  aDollar Price.  aEconomic forces.  aEconomics.  aEconomist.  aEmployment.  aExchange rate.  aFixed exchange-rate system.  aForay.  aFraud.  aGary S. Becker.  aGeorge Stigler.  aHuman capital.  aIncome distribution.  aIncome.  aIndustrialisation.  aInflation.  aInfrastructure.  aJohn F. Kennedy.  aJorge Alessandri.  aLatin America.  aLouis Rougier.  aLudwig Erhard.  aMarket economy.  aMichael Polanyi.  aMilton Friedman.  aMiracle of Chile.  aNeoliberalism.  aNobel Prize.  aOrlando Letelier.  aPatricio Aylwin.  aPension.  aPolicy.  aPrivate sector.  aProtectionism.  aPublic sphere.  aRetirement savings account.  aRicardo Lagos.  aSalvador Allende.  aSecondary sector of the economy.  aSophistication.  aTalca.  aTariff.  aThe Best and the Brightest.  aThe Birth of Biopolitics.  aTrade barrier.  aWorld Economic Outlook.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2023 Englishz978311131907008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE